Sturm, Ruger & Company, Inc. (NYSE: RGR) is excited to introduce the RugerÂ® SR1911Â® Lightweight Commander-Style pistol; an aluminum frame version of the popular SR1911 Commander-Style pistol. This new model features a black anodized aluminum frame with a satin stainless finish on the slide, resulting in an attractive two-tone appearance in a gun that weighs 7oz. less than the all stainless steel version. It comes factory equipped with an integrated, polished titanium feed ramp and features thin, hardwood grip panels for concealed carry, as well as front strap serrations for improved grip. Ruger engineers took a hard look at how they could utilize new materials to improve the performance of the aluminum-framed 1911. Most aluminum frame pistols tend to show excessive wear on the feed ramp, particularly when shooting modern hollow-point ammunition. This can result in unreliable feeding and may be expensive to correct. The new SR1911 Lightweight Commander-Style pistol comes factory equipped with an integrated polished titanium feed ramp for a lifetime of reliable performance. Since entering the 1911 market in 2011, Ruger has quickly become known for producing some of the best quality 1911's available today. These American-made, CNC machined, series-70 design 1911's come standard with many features typically found only in custom manufactured pistols. All SR1911's feature Novak LoMount Carry 3-dot sights, a lowered and flared ejection port, and a titanium firing pin. In addition, each Ruger SR1911 features a precision barrel and bushing which are machined to match from the same piece of bar stock. The frames have an integral plunger tube, beaver-tail grip safety, oversized magazine release, extended thumb safety and a skeletonized hammer and trigger for fast, accurate shooting. All of this, without the price tag of a custom gun. With the addition of this aluminum frame, commander-style model to the SR1911 line, customers now have a lightweight carry option with the rugged reliability of a Ruger. The SR1911 Lightweight Commander-Style pistol features a 4.25" barrel and weighs 29.3 oz. with an empty magazine. It ships with two 7-round magazines, a bushing wrench, cable locking device, and a soft case.

postcontent: Seller Stock #: LG31046T Here is what our photographer calls a Texas Mossberg. Manufacturer is Maverick Arms of Eagle Pass, Texas, part of Mossberg. Construction is steel barrel, magazine tube, bolt, and internal parts assembled into a lightweight alloy receiver based on the tried and true 500 series Mossbergs. Type is pump or slide action shotgun. The Maverick 88 has double steel slide bars like both its parent and arch competitor Remington 870. Trigger housing is high impact polymer like the parent 500. Safety is non reversible for right hand shooter, mounted just forward of the trigger. Slide release is on the triggerâs left side as the photos show. Chambering is 12 gauge, 2 3/4 inch and 3 inch shells interchangeably. Barrel is 20 inch .722 vicinity Cylinder Bore, capable of handling any loads from steel shot to rifled slugs. Sight is conventional hex base brass. We have outfitted the barrel with a polymer vented heat shield, somewhat on the order of the blue steel shields that came on the famous Winchester 97 Trench Guns. Magazine is full length steel, holds up to 7 each 2 3/4 inch shells, or 6 each 3 inch; fully loaded capacity is 7 + 1 on 2 3/4 inch. This shotgun will accept Mossberg 500 barrels whose lugs are positioned for a 7 shot magazine, 18 3/4 inches clearance between the receiver and the lug. Stock and forend are graphite based black synthetic. Forend is classic corn cob police type. Buttstock length of pull measures 14 1/2 inches from the trigger face to the end of the 1 inch recoil pad, with a 3/4 inch right hand cant. Weight empty is 6 pounds 9 ounces, with center of gravity at the breech face, or approximately 7 1/2 pounds loaded with Winchester 3 inch OO Buck. Overall length is a compact 40 1/2 inches. title: For Sale:  Radom 9x18 Model P83 Wanad Polish Federal Police P-83 9mm Makarov 9 shot Lucznik Poland 1987-89 Holster, Rod, 1 Magazin
postcontent: Seller Stock #: HGP83U This Pistol is Not C&R Eligible. Photos are representative on this listing, but buyer will receive a virtually identical specimen, at least as good as the photos. Dealers, departments, and collectors, however, may take any similar P83s we have on hand at the same per-pistol price, and with no additional shipping charges. Photos show one of relatively few Polish Radom model P-83s Wanad pistols to come into the country. These are well made steel frame compact pistols on the order of the Mauser HSC. Manufacturer is Lucznik Arms Factory of Radom, Poland. Manufacture dates on the ones we have ranged between 1987 and 1989. Importer is PW Arms, marking on the left side of the slide. The P83 served with the Polish military in the Gulf War and in the Balkans, from its introduction in 1983 until its replacement some 17 years later. These served in Southwest Poland, Dolnoslaskie Province. Type is double- and single-action blowback semi-auto pistol. Construction is entirely vanadium steel metal, with dark semi gloss blue finish. Chambering is 9x18, 9mm Makarov. This pistol will Not chamber or digest 9mm Luger caliber ammunition. We have Russian 9mm Makarov ammunition readily available. Barrel is 3 1/2 inch, four groove right hand 1:9.83 rifling. Slide is serrated rear, .965 wide with axial dovetailed blade front sight and drift only windage adjustable dovetailed rear steel sight. Safety is slide mounted on the left side, for a right handed shooter. It serves as a decocker with some effort, and the P-83 safety is opposite from a Walther. Fire is down and safe is forward. The P83 does not have a firing pin safety or magazine safety. Double Action Trigger pull is 15 pound vicinity with 1 inch travels, and single action is 6 pound area with 1/2 inch travel and moderate felt creep. Overall length is 6 1/16 inches from the muzzle to the edge of the grip frame strut. Height is 4 3/4 inches from the top of the rear sight to the lowest portion of the magazine floorplate. Trigger is .310 serrated face alloy, with .360 serrated spur steel hammer. Photo specimen pulled at 15 pounds double action, and 6 pounds single action, two stage with moderate felt creep; 1 inch travel on double action and half that on single action. Disassembly is steyr style, with a drop down disassembly plate positioned forward of the trigger. Weight empty is 25 1/2 ounces with center of gravity at the slide stop. Magazine is factory Radom, holds 8 rounds of 9x18 Makarov Caliber ammunition, 8+1 total loaded capacity. Magazine release is on the butt, European style. Holster is genuine leather with cleaning tool inside and with an extra magazine compartment. Surface detractions are moderate, with occasional whitening from holster contact and occasional finish freckling. We rate these pistols as Very Good, 80 percent vicinity by our estimate. Bore, chamber and mechanism are all bright and clean. From our inspection, we estimate these pistols have been fired fewer than 500 rounds. title: For Sale:  6.8mm SPC AR 15 w/scope & Laser
postcontent:
This is a custom built AR using Anderson Lower with an Armalite tactical two-stage trigger set and Ambidextrous Safety for those who are left-handed. I choose the 6.8mm over the 5.56 or 7.62 for a variety of reasons. It is a heavier bullet and you get a better kill shot if you have to go through a little brush or your shot is off just a bit. I'd also rather have it with wild hogs than the 5.56.
I put an AIM 2.5X10X40 higher end scope on it with an added green laser. These have been bore sighted but no rounds have been fired through the gun yet. I've stockpiled 180 rounds of ammo for it in an ammo can.
I am selling this sweat rifle because I've had some very unexpected expenses and am in need of some rapid cash. I cannot give the gun away but it is going to feel like it to me after all the time and work in selecting parts and assembling it using the American Gunsmithing Institute's AR 15 Armorer's Course and AR 15 Trigger Job Course. I also have two mags for it and a good soft AR 15 case.

Sorry about not having a picture, my camera will not upload to my computer now.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1940's Nazi Marked Browning Hi-Power 9mm P-35 German Occupation Army WWII - Bring Back trophy in NICKEL! Beautiful piece!
postcontent:
DESCRIPTION: This is a very beautiful old Belgium made Browning produced during Nazi control. It is marked "The Fabrique Nationale d'Armes de Guerre" (French for National Factory of Weapons of War). It is a German Occupational Army pistol with matching serial numbers on the frame, slide and barrel. Both also have the Nazi Eagle over Swastika proof marks and designation of AaW140. A great piece of history with matching serial numbers. I have shot this pistol and it shoots like a dream. After shooting it I took it down and gave it a very thorough cleaning.
This was likely removed from a soldier and brought to America years ago. Someone during that period had it a gunsmith nickel their trophy, and that is great because you can tell this was done during that time period and not a recent nickel job, making this more authentic to the real story. What a conversation piece!

BROWNING HISTORIAN: After contacting Glen, the Browning historian it was determined these pistols were produced for the German Occupational Army between 1940-1944. With limited records, it is difficult to determine the exact date.

PROOF MARKINGS: The frame is marked with the German Eagle over swastika. Also the WaA140 acceptance mark, and the right side has the serial number â156949â. The barrel is marked with an âEagleâ and â156949â and the WaA140.

GRIPS: These appear to the be correct walnut grips in authentic condition for their age. Checkering still present and in good condition. Has some dings etc as expected from an authentic pistol of this vintage.

SLIDE: Slide is in reasonable condition for it's age. Serial numbers match the frame and the barrel.


BARREL: Approximately 4 3/4" barrel with good bore and rifling.


ACTION: Very smooth and crisp action. This was test fired and worked well for me.


MAGAZINE: This appears to be the correct slotted base magazine.


HISTORY: FN commissioned John Browning to design a new military sidearm conforming to this specification. Browning had previously sold the rights to his successful M1911 U.S. Army automatic pistol to Colt's Patent Firearms, and was therefore forced to design an entirely new pistol while working around the M1911 patents. Browning built two different prototypes for the project in Utah and filed the patent for this pistol in the United States on June 28, 1923 and granted on February 22, 1927.[5][6] One was a simple blowback design, while the other was operated with a locked-breech recoil system. Both prototypes utilized the new staggered magazine design (by designer DieudonnÃ© Saive) to increase capacity without unduly increasing the pistol's grip size or magazine length. By 1931, the Hi-Power design incorporated a shortened 13-round magazine, a curved rear grip strap, and a bar.

title: For Sale:  COMPOUND BOW PACKAGE! Ready to Hunt! Martin Firecat TR2 *PRICE DROP*
postcontent:
I'm selling my Martin Firecat TR2 (Pro X riser with TR2 limbs and Cat 2 cams). The bow is in excellent shape, and is extremely fast and accurate!

Last year I had a new Hammerhead string installed and tuned (timed, synched) by Atlantic Game and Tackle, but haven't hunted with the bow at all since then. I got it sighted in over 2 range days, and that's all. The slide was replaced as well as the arrow rest (whisker biscuit) and the dampener. They also set me up with 4 brand new arrows. The bow is 60-70 lbs draw weight, 26-30" draw length, 32.25" ATA, 7" BH, and rated at 335-345 fps IBO. The bow is currently set at 70 lb draw weight with 80% let off (also adjustable), and 29" draw length.

The bow comes with a brand new Flambeau hard case, a quiver, 4 new carbon arrows, a Copper John Dead Nuts 2 sight, a new Whisker Biscuit arrow rest, a release, built in limb savers (riser dampeners and arrow shelf dampener), and a ShotBlocker Pro Shot target that can handle both field points and broadheads.

This is a great setup, but I just haven't been hunting recently and don't see myself getting to go much in the future. This is great for anyone looking to get into the bowhunting game, or someone looking to upgrade to a faster bow (believe me, this bow is FAST).

Please let me know if you have any questions or want to check the bow out in person.
